House Selling Prices

pacman::p_load(
  tidyverse,
  pander,
  car,
  Saunders
)

clean <- read.csv("train.csv")

# mutations meant to simplify graphs
# Reduces number of Overall Quality and Neighborhood groups
train <- clean %>% mutate(
  GeneralQual = if_else(OverallQual < 7, "<7", as.character(OverallQual)),
  ) %>% 
  left_join(
    clean %>% group_by(Neighborhood) %>% 
      summarize(
        Med = median(SalePrice)
      ) %>% 
      ungroup() %>% 
      mutate(
        NbhdType = case_when(
          Med < 125000 ~ "Very Low",
          Med < 175000 ~ "Low",
          Med < 250000 ~ "Mid",
          Med > 250000 ~ "High",
          .default = "Unknown"
        )
      ),
    
    by = "Neighborhood"
  )

# Linear Model
mylm <- lm(SalePrice ~ TotRmsAbvGrd + TotRmsAbvGrd:GeneralQual + GrLivArea:NbhdType, train)
b <- mylm$coef

# Display Model Summary
# mylm %>% summary() %>% pander()


# Prepare for graphing
# Just the min and max GrLivArea because they are used a few times
minmax <- c(min(train$GrLivArea), max(train$GrLivArea))

# Data manipulation to plot the linear model lines
for_lines <- data.frame()
for (gq in unique(train$GeneralQual)) {
  for (nb in unique(train$NbhdType)) {
      for (gr in minmax) {
        for_lines = rbind(for_lines, data.frame(
          GrLivArea = gr,
          GeneralQual = gq,
          NbhdType = nb
        ))
      
    }
  }
}

# Continued
for_lines <- for_lines %>% mutate(
  TotRmsAbvGrd = -1000,
  ymin = predict(mylm, data.frame(GrLivArea, GeneralQual, TotRmsAbvGrd = 2, NbhdType)),
  ymax = predict(mylm, data.frame(GrLivArea, GeneralQual, TotRmsAbvGrd = 14, NbhdType)),
  SalePrice = ymin
)

Commentary

Overview

Hoping to predict house selling prices with Kaggle.com competition data, I tried various linear models, many of which are high dimensional, and settled on a model that explains above 80% of the variation in price. This model uses ground living area, rooms above ground, quality rating, and neighborhood, which is grouped by median household income to reduce model complexity.

As a point of weakness, looking at this model, either from the mathematical equation or from the graph is not very clear. It needs interpretation to be understood. With that backdrop, here is the model:

\[ \underbrace{\hat{Y_i}}_\text{Pred. Sale Price} = 98759 + -5214 \underbrace{X_{1i}}_{\text{ Total Rooms} \\ \text{Above Ground}} + 17315 X_{1i} \underbrace{X_{2i}}_{\ \text{Quality} \\ \text{Score 10}} + 3417 X_{1i} \underbrace{X_{2i}}_{\text{Quality} \\ \text{Score 7}} + 7784 X_{1i} \underbrace{X_{2i}}_{\text{Quality} \\ \text{Score 8}} + 16003 X_{1i} \underbrace{X_{2i}}_{\text{Quality} \\ \text{Score 9}} + \\ \quad\quad\quad\;\; 90.57 \underbrace{X_{3i}}_{\text{Above Ground} \\ \;\: \text{Living Area}} \underbrace{X_{4i}}_{\;\; \text{Neighborhood} \\ \;\;\; \text{Income High}} + 74.01 X_{3i} \underbrace{X_{4i}}_{\text{Neighborhood} \\ \; \text{Income Low}} + 57.14 X_{3i} \underbrace{X_{4i}}_{\text{Neighborhood} \\ \; \text{Income Mid}} + 37.5 X_{3i} \underbrace{X_{4i}}_{\text{Neighborhood} \\ \quad \text{Income} \\ \;\; \text{Very Low}} \]

ggplot(train, aes(GrLivArea / 1000, SalePrice / 1000, color = factor(NbhdType, c("High", "Mid", "Low", "Very Low")))) +

  geom_ribbon(data = for_lines, aes(ymin = ymin / 1000, ymax = ymax / 1000, fill = factor(NbhdType, c("High", "Mid", "Low", "Very Low"))), alpha = 0.2) +
  facet_wrap(~factor(GeneralQual, levels = c("<7", "7", "8", "9", "10"))) +

  ) +
  theme_minimal()

To explain this model, lets pull out a few key insights:

1. The Slope is Up

The base slope coefficient \(\beta_1 = -5214\) signifies that for every additional room above ground, the price goes down $5,214. However, it is not the only coefficient, and it is not the largest. All other coefficients are positive and in most practical cases well offset the negative \(\beta_1\). Larger living area, quality rating of the home, and higher median income neighborhoods all increase the price of the home. This can be seen well in the above graph. So how can we interpret the negative \(\beta_1\)?

2. Less Rooms are Better for Low Quality Homes

\(\beta_1\) singles out homes that are low quality (below 7). As the quality score increases, that switches to positive. A quality score of 7 (\(\beta_3\)) adds $3,417 to the slope, equaling -$1,797. For every additional room above ground in a quality 7 home, the predicted price goes down by $1,797. For a quality 10 home (\(\beta_2\)), the price increases $12,101 for every additional room.

One way to see this on the graph is the flip of 2 rooms and 14 rooms. At lower quality levels, the 14 is below 2, and it flips to 14 above 2. This flip matches the explanation of the negative base coefficient tied to increasing interaction terms.

3. Living Area and Neighborhood are Equally or More Impactful

Although coefficients such as \(\beta_9 = 37.5\) and \(\beta_6 = 90.57\) are remarkably lower than previous terms like \(\beta_2 = 17315\), it helps to recognize what they are tied to. Living area is better measure in 100s or 1000s. \(\beta_0\) states that for every 100 square foot increase, sale price increases $3,750, and for every 1,000 square feet, it increases by $37,500. For the high income neighborhoods, the sale price increases $90,570 per 1,000 square feet.

Visually, there is a very strong tie between living are and sale price, and a dramatic shift in slope from one neighborhood to another, with higher neighborhoods having higher slope.

Model

All P-values in this model are highly significant. The standard errors are practically large, which is not ideal for exact prediction. The adjusted \(R^2 = 0.8207\) meaning the model explains 82% of the variation in Sale Price.

Validation

While this only shows one random seed, this model does usually predict about 80% after trying multiple random predictions. By taking a portion of the data to fit the model and a portion to predict with, we can see the models effectiveness on new data.

set.seed(122)

num_rows <- 1000 #1460 total
keep <- sample(1:nrow(train), num_rows)

mytrain <- train[keep, ] #Use this in the lm(..., data=mytrain) it is like "rbdata"

mytest <- train[-keep, ] #Use this in the predict(..., newdata=mytest) it is like "rbdata2"

mylm <- lm(SalePrice ~ TotRmsAbvGrd + TotRmsAbvGrd:GeneralQual + GrLivArea:NbhdType, mytrain)
yhat <- predict(mylm, newdata = mytest)
ybar <- mean(mytest$SalePrice)
SSTO <- sum((mytest$SalePrice - ybar)^2)
SSE <- sum((mytest$SalePrice - yhat)^2)
r2 <- 1 - SSE / SSTO

# Trying to make a function that runs all the above code
# I would have to identify the column (eg. mytest$SalePrice)
# test_r2 <- function(model, test_data) {
#   yhat <- predict(mylm, newdata = test_data)
#   ybar <- mean(mytest)
#   SSTO <- (test_data - ybar)^2
#   SSE <- (yhat - ybar)^2
#   r2 <- SSE / SSTO
# }

adjusted_r2 <- function(r2, n, p) {
  1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - p - 1))
}

adjr2 <- adjusted_r2(r2, nrow(mytest), 3)

tribble(
  ~Measure, ~Value,
  "Train R^2", round(summary(mylm)$r.squared, 3),
  "Test R^2", round(r2, 3),
  "Adjusted R^2:", round(adjr2, 3)
) %>% pander()

        Med < 175000 ~ "Low",
